[2] Belgium, biosecurity measures
Date: Thu 4 Oct 2018
Source: dhnet (Belgium) [in French, machine transl., edited]
http://www.dhnet.be/regions/luxembourg/accident-avec-un-sanglier-que-faire-dans-la-zone-infectee-5bb4d74bcd70d3638daede08


Since 17 Sep 2018, the date the ministerial decree prohibiting traffic in forests to limit the spread of the African swine fever was enforced, within a perimeter of 63 000 hectares (about 244 square miles), the police of Gaume counted several accidents caused by wild boars in the infected area.

"In our police zone, there are about 600 accidents a year; 150 are caused by game," says the divisional commissioner Jean-Yves Schul. "In recent weeks, some accidents caused by wild boars have been noted, including in the commune of Meix-devant-Virton, [but] all may not have been reported."

The commanding officer recommends calling the police so that adequate measures are taken. "If it's a wild boar, it's very important to report it to limit the spread of the virus," he says, "Do not approach or touch the animal. To report the facts and the position of the vehicle, we must wait for the arrival of a police service on site, [and] we recommend not to touch the outside of the vehicle and secure or report its location if is on the road."

The procedure set up in the context of the crisis foresees that a police team will go on site to assess the situation and, if necessary, ask for assistance from the Nature and Forests Division. "If necessary, the vehicle can be decontaminated directly or retrospectively," he concludes, "Virkon is a disinfectant approved by the University of Liege, and the carcass of the wild boar is then analyzed."

In the case where the struck animal is not a wild boar, the user is invited to follow the procedure of declaration of the usual accident at the police station.

[Byline: Nadia Lallemant]

