Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The ASF event in the Belgian province of Luxembourg, adjacent to the borders of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg and France, is continuing in an increased pace, though limited to its initial declared infected zone. As underlined in section [3], the Belgian farmers demand applying a control and eventual eradication policy in line with the Czech policy.

Subscribers are referred to the presentation "African swine fever in wild boars in the Czech Republic -- current situation" presented during the most recent meeting of EU's Standing Committee on Plants, Animals, Food and Feed -- sections Animal Health and Welfare and Controls and Import Conditions, held in Brussels on 19 Sep 2018.

The presentation covered the period between 26 Jun 2017 (start of event) and 18 Sep 2018. In total, 230 cases of ASF were recorded in the wild boar population, of which 212 were found in dead wild boar and 18 hunted wild boar. The last positive cases were found in hunted wild boar on 8 Feb 2018 and in dead wild boar on 15 Apr 2018. All the positive cases were limited to the declared "high-risk area" (only 89 square km/about 34 square miles). There was not a single case in domestic pigs. For additional information, including maps and tables/graphics, please refer to https://ec.europa.eu/food/sites/food/files/animals/docs/reg-com_ahw_20180919_pres_asf_cze.pdf.

The Czech Republic sent its follow-up report No. 35 on the ASF event on 1 Oct 2018. Although no new cases have been recorded since the previous follow-up report (submitted 20 Apr 2018), the event has not been declared "resolved," and is regarded as "continuing."

A summary of the event, including a map and links to all follow-up reports, is available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review/viewsummary?fupser=&dothis=&reportid=24159.

OIE's Handbook on "African swine fever in wild boar and biosecurity during hunting," version 25 Sep 2018, is available at https://tinyurl.com/ya7eqztj. - Mod.AS

